Bye bye to accident with new operation Tsuruoka police station and related organizations to raise safety awareness | Yamagata Shimbun
At a bicycle class held as the start event of the operation, a collision experiment between a car and a bicycle was conducted = Shoko Gakuen Driving School in Tsuruoka City
In recent years, the Tsuruoka Police Station (Chief Sato Keizo) has launched the "Bye Bye Accident Zero Operation" in an attempt to eliminate accidents involving bicycles and motorcycles, which have a high rate of occurrence in the area.
In addition to working with traffic safety organizations in the area to raise awareness of accident prevention, they will also strengthen the crackdown on bicycle traffic rule violations.
There have been three traffic fatalities in the jurisdiction of the station this year, with motorcyclists and cyclists killed.
Although the number of accidents has been on a decreasing trend, the rate of accidents involving bicycles was about 11.7% as of June 30, and that involving motorcycles was about 5.8%, both higher than the prefectural average.
In particular, the rate of bicycle accidents in the past five years has often exceeded the prefectural average, and we planned a strategy to overcome this situation.
The name of the operation is "bike" and "bicycle" multiplied by the meaning of eradicating accidents.
Related organizations will be encouraged more than ever to provide driving guidance to the elderly and use night light reflective materials in traffic safety classes.
The station issues yellow cards (guidance warning tickets) in the event of a crackdown to warn people.
The opening ceremony of the operation was held on the 21st at Shoko Gakuen Driving School in Tsuruoka City.
About 30 people involved attended, and Chief Sato said, "I would like to ask for your cooperation to reduce even one tragic accident."
A representative from the station showed the policy and the activities of each organization.
A bicycle class was held as the start of the operation.
A police officer in a car demonstrated how the impact on a bicycle differs between hitting a bicycle with the brakes applied and hitting it at about 55 km / h without stepping on the brakes.
Kaneuchi Hiroshi, chairman of the Tsuruoka Regional Traffic Safety Activities Promotion Committee, said, "I realized once again the horror of traffic accidents, and I would like to call attention not only to the elderly but also to young people."
